In the figure below, $AB=15,$ $AC=14,$ and $BY=12$. Compute $CX$.
\begin{center}
\begin{asy}
size(6cm);
pair a=(495/13,840/13); pair b=(0,0); pair c=(65,0);
dot(a); dot(b); dot(c);
pair x=(33/75)*a;
pair y=(5/14)*(a-c)+c;
dot(x); dot(y);
draw(c--b--a--c);
draw(x--c,dashed);
draw(b--y,dashed);
draw(x+(c-x)/11.2--x+(c-x)/11.2+(a-x)/8.4--x+(a-x)/8.4);
draw(y+(c-y)/5--y+(c-y)/5+(b-y)/12--y+(b-y)/12);
label("$A$",a,N);
label("$B$",b,SW);
label("$C$",c,SE);
label("$X$",x,WNW);
label("$Y$",y,ENE);

\end{asy}
\end{center}

\textbf{Answer:} $BY$ and $AC$ are a base and corresponding height of the triangle; $AB$ and $CX$ are another base-height pair.  Therefore, the product of $BY$ and $AC$ should be the same as the product of $AB$ and $CX$.  Assigning the variable $x$ to length $CX$, we have: $$14\cdot12=15\cdot x$$ and finally $x=\boxed{11.2}$.
